{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/create-a-youtube-video-from-code-c9b433485d72", "time": 1683004224.254124, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/create-a-youtube-video-from-code-c9b433485d72/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Create a YouTube Video from Code. With a C++ demo to create a fractal\u2026 | by Don Cross | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Create a YouTube Video from Code", "description": "Write C++ code to generate a series of PNG images. Convert the images to an MP4 video using the ffmpeg program. You can upload the video to YouTube."}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mandelbrot_set", "anchor_text": "Mandelbrot Set", "paragraph_index": 3}, {"url": "https://github.com/cosinekitty/mandelzoom/blob/master/mandelzoom.cpp", "anchor_text": "mandelzoom.cpp", "paragraph_index": 5}, {"url": "https://github.com/cosinekitty/raytrace", "anchor_text": "ray tracer", "paragraph_index": 13}, {"url": "http://cosinekitty.com/raytrace/", "anchor_text": "Fundamentals of Ray Tracing", "paragraph_index": 13}], "all_paragraphs": ["If you are a computer programmer who has ever thought of creating a video that contains a computer-generated animation, this article is for you. Here I will assume that you have existing code, or can write code, that creates some kind of image as a two-dimensional array of pixels. It doesn\u2019t matter what kind of image it is, so long as it fits in an array in memory.", "If you can get to that point, this article will take you the rest of the way. You will learn the step-by-step details of how to create an MP4 video file. When we are done, you will have a video file suitable for upload to YouTube, like this one:", "Here is an outline of the steps for creating a computer-generated video.", "The Mandelbrot Set is one of the most famous fractal objects. The above video gradually increases the magnification of the Mandelbrot Set from a factor of 1 up to a factor of 100 million. The video spans 30 seconds, at a rate of 30 frames per second, for a total of 900 images played in rapid succession.", "It is remarkable that so much visual complexity emerges from iterating the tiny formula", "The Mandelbrot function in the source file mandelzoom.cpp iterates this formula until either the complex z value goes outside a circle of radius 2 from the origin, or n (the iteration count) reaches a maximum limit. The resulting value of n determines the color of a given pixel on the screen.", "Take a look at the function Palette to see how the iteration count is converted into red, green, and blue color values.", "The function GenerateZoomFrames produces a series of PNG output files. Each PNG file contains a Mandelbrot Set image rendered at a different magnification. The frame images have a resolution of 1280 pixels wide by 720 pixels high, which is a standard HD 720p video size.", "For your own video generator application, the class VideoFrame may be helpful. It represents a single frame of video and knows how to save the frame as a PNG file. The function GenerateZoomFrames uses VideoFrame to generate each frame of the fractal zoom movie.", "The member function VideoFrame::SetPixel must be called by your application for every pixel of every frame. You pass in a PixelColor struct that defines the red, green, and blue color components of the pixel. These value are all integers in the range 0..255.", "PixelColor also contains an alpha value in the range 0..255 indicating how transparent the pixel is. For video applications, you should always set this to 255, meaning that the pixel is completely opaque. I included the alpha value for generality, in case you want to generate PNG files that have transparent regions.", "I include a bash script run that automates the entire process of building the mandelzoom program from source code, running it, and converting the resulting 900 PNG files to a movie file called zoom.mp4. This last step is accomplished by running the program ffmpeg. Here is the run script. It includes some helpful comments explaining the command line arguments to ffmpeg.", "And that\u2019s all there is to it! You can download the entire source code repository mandelzoom using the link in the \u201cReferences\u201d section at the end of this article.", "I mentioned that this technique can be used for creating any kind of video you can imagine, so long as you can write the code to create each frame. Just for fun, I conclude with another sample YouTube video I created. It is based on a simple ray tracer I created for my book Fundamentals of Ray Tracing. The code that created this video works the same way as the Mandelbrot zoomer above: it generates a series of PNG files that ffmpeg then converts into an MP4 file.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes."], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2Fc9b433485d72&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fcreate-a-youtube-video-from-code-c9b433485d72&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fcreate-a-youtube-video-from-code-c9b433485d72&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign In"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fnew-story&source=---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------new_post_sidenav-----------", "anchor_text": "Write"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/search?source